TY  - JOUR
T1  - Decision Centralization and Learning from Experience in Groups: Separating Context from Aggregation Effects
AU  - Park, Sanghyun
AU  - Gonzalez, Cleotilde
AU  - Puranam, Phanish
Y1  - 2024/11/22
PY  - 2024
DA  - 2025/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2022.01507
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2022.01507
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 6859
EP  - 6879
VL  - 71
IS  - 8
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Organizational learning often involves groups that learn from feedback on their decisions over time (also known as ?learning by doing? or ?learning from experience?). Although organizational learning is frequently assumed to resemble individual learning from experience, there is limited evidence to validate this assumption. Furthermore, groups in organizations often have centralized rather than decentralized decision making, but we know little about how they differ in learning from experience. Using a combination of experimental data and computational modeling, we compare individuals to groups that are either decentralized or centralized in their decision making. We find that centralized groups behave like hyper-individuals: They update and explore more than individuals (who, in turn, update and explore more than decentralized groups). Our evidence shows that not only do groups differ from individuals because of aggregation processes but also that individuals change their behaviors simply by virtue of being in a group (a context effect). Specifically, we find that participants assigned as leaders in centralized groups become proactive learners who seek novel information to learn by deviating from experience. Implications are drawn for how this might alter the way we conceptualize and model organizational learning.This paper was accepted by Olav Sorenson, organization.Funding: This work was supported by the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency [Grant W911NF-20-1-0006], the Strategic Management Society [Will Mitchell Dissertation Research Grant Program], NUS Presidential Young Professorship grant and the Desmarais Fund for the Organizations and Algorithms project.Supplemental Material: The online appendix and data files are available at https://doi.org/10.1287/mnsc.2022.01507.
